--- !u!114 &1691619225
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1691619221}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: a43aa686be69a0c468cf8f09157ac84e, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  phrases:
  - I can't see a thing! Press L to turn the lights on!
  - That's better.
  - Let's see how we can illuminate scenes in Unity. (Press L to continue)
  - 'Unity has two types of lighting: real-time and baked. We will only discuss real-time,
    but you''re welcome to read about baked lighting in the Unity docs. (Press L
    to continue)'
  - Imagine real-time lights as simple "shapes" of light, which illuminate all they
    intersect, creating (hard) shadows and making objects visible. (Press L to continue)
  - These here are Spot Lights. Imagine these are cones of light (such as street
    lamps, or the Bat-signal). Try creating some and edit them to see how they work!
    (Press L to continue)
  - On the other side of the room, you will find some Point Lights. These are spherical
    lights that are great for creating interesting shadows. Think candles, or small
    light bulbs. Try them! (Press L to continue)
  - Here's a Directional Light. This type of light has no origin, it lights everything
    with a given angle. This is what you use to model the sun. Try it by editing
    the "Directional Light" object  in the Hierarchy. (Press L to continue)
  - Another interesting way of lighting scenes is using Emissive objects, but we'll
    discuss it later. (Press L to continue)
  - 'EXERCISE 1: Write a script for Room 2 > Hanging Light so that its Spot Light
    follows me while I''m moving! (Press L to continue)'
  - After completing, please proceed to the exit.
  - Those interns forgot to setup a skybox again! We'll do it ourselves. (Press L
    to continue)
  - Go to Window > Rendering > Lighting. Then select "Environment" from the top boxes
    and choose the "Skybox" asset in the "Skybox Material" parameter. (Press L to
    continue)
  - Much better now! Proceed to the next room.
  - Before moving to shading, let's take a quick look at cameras. (Press L to continue)
  - Create a Camera GameObject. Unity scenes can have any number of Cameras. (Press
    L to continue)
  - Play around with the settings in the Camera > Projection component. These control
    how the 3D objects are mapped to the 2D camera/image space. (Press L to continue)
  - 'EXERCISE 2: Parent the new Camera to the Lab > Room 4 > Security Cam object.
    Write a script with two functionalities: 1) the camera should look at the Character
    object. 2) When the button "F" is pressed, Unity should switch the active camera
    between the Main Camera object and the new Camera you created. (Press L to continue)'
  - 'Once you''re done, open the next scene: 2_Shading. See you soon!'
